1. What is the command to initialize a git repository?

a) git pull b) git clone c) git push d) git init

Ans: git init

2. Initialize a git repository at /home/sarah/story-blog
Create directory if it doesn't already exist.

Hint: Run mkdir /home/sarah/story-blog to create directory and then run cd /home/sarah/story-blog; git init

3. Which hidden folder gets created after initializing a git repository?

Hint: Run ls -la inside /home/sarah/story-blog directory to see hidden folders

Ans: .git

4. Once a git repository has been initialized, which stage contains the active changes in your local git repository?

a) Pushed files b) Working area c) Committed files d) Staging Area 

Hint: All files in a GIT Repo just initialized are in the Working Area

5. Letâ€™s add a file to our project inside /home/sarah/story-blog

File name: lion-and-mouse.txt

File content: A Lion lay asleep in the forest

Hint: Run touch lion-and-mouse.txt; echo "A Lion lay asleep in the forest" >> lion-and-mouse.txt

6. Which stage contains new changes that will soon be committed to local git repo ?

Hint: Files that are added are moved to the Staging Area

7. Configure git when using for the first time

Hint: Run cd /home/sarah/story-blog; git config user.email sarah@example.com;git config user.name sarah


8. Adding the file notes.txt to .gitignore

echo notes.txt >> .gitignore













